title: Do you agree that humans are already using technology in ways that conceivably affect evolution? - Quora

response.answer_text: Hell yes. To have a glimpse of those effects on our biology, you need to look no further than the Dopamine Desensitization. Dopamine is known as the pleasure molecule. In healthy humans, it is produced by the body in anticipation of food, sex or any other activity that would benefit the human’s survival or the reproduction of his genes. Whenever this chemical is produced, the person feels a pleasure sensation. This is the body’s way to reward the person, ensuring him that whatever he’s doing at the time being is good, and to encourage him to repeat the activity in the future. This body reward system is very important, since it keeps us motivated to seek the activities that are of true benefit to us. The problem, however, is that in modern times, technology has reshaped our environment in ways for which evolution has not prepared us. The dopamine receptors in our brains are now being bombarded with dopamine molecules in levels higher than what was normal in our pre-modern times. These levels are generated by everyday activities, some of which are known to be harmful, whereas others we regard as benign. The dangerous outcome of this is what is called Dopamine Desensitization. This happens when the sensitivity of the dopamine receptors in the brain gets reduced, so as to accommodate to the abnormally high influx of dopamine. As a result, we lose all motivation to seek the fundamental activities that are necessary for us. People now prefer to have processed food rather than real natural food; Some prefer to hunch down on smartphones scrolling down their social media feed rather than socialize in real life; Some don’t even bother asking a girl out when they know that they can always call on their favorite adult site once they get to their home; All this and more (Alcohol and drug use, video games…) contribute to the desensitization of dopamine receptors. These shifts in our preferences are contrary to our biology. They mess with the very core of our nature. And nothing good can come out of it. We can not simply dismiss millions of years of biological evolution for the sake of recent technological evolution.

It would be difficult to disagree. Humans have existed as genus Homo, to use our own conceited and self-assigned definition, for at least 2 million years. During all of that time evidence may be found for increasingly complex human-conceived and purpose-fashioned technologies, especially stone tools, but also food processing, including soaking, scraping, grinding and cooking. And so on. From all of which we may infer many other tools and techniques, including tools that did not fossilise easily or at all, and skills and techniques such as the mastery of fire. All of which constitutes the “technology” of the times, places, and populations involved. Given that these technologies were demonstrably in use, and that they too “evolved” or changed over time, it is reasonable to infer that the tools themselves, by their utility and use, affected, influenced and interacted to help sort, differentiate and propagate traits in human populations. They offered survival value, or not, and thus influenced behavioural responses to selective forces. The distributions of genes and phenotypes we see in the fossil record, and that we can infer from genetic reconstruction and allied phylogeny, supports this view. Given that Homo sapiens arrived as a self-defined species only fairly recently, within the last 300,000 years, reinforces that view. That we became “behaviourally modern” only within the last 120,000 years or so only strengthens the case. There is no reason to think that our changing tool-kit of technologies is no longer influencing our evolution, or the change in distribution of heritable traits. That human populations migrated out of Africa (in several waves, perhaps beginning with Homo erectus) and has surged from mere millions into the billions, is clearly correlated with technological innovations including agriculture, transportation, clothing, language, medicine, and much more. All of these factors and technologies are playing out in changing populations of traits within human populations globally, even today. In the future, assuming we get that far, space travel and dispersal of human populations into areas exposed to different levels of radiation and gravity may well influence trait selection in new ways. That technology would play a part in our (potential) future off-Earth dispersal is obvious enough. That our medical and nutritional knowledge and many other technologies influences trait persistence and propagation here on Earth, right now, is also a given (in my view, anyway). So yes, I can’t disagree.

We have been doing that since before we became Homo Sapiens Socialising is an inheritable trait. Knowledge is an inheritable trait. Language is an inheritable trait. Writing is an inheritable trait. All of these traits increases a tribe’s fitness, and makes it easier for them to thrive and procreate.  The theory of Evolution only says that a trait needs a) increase fitness and b) be inherited. It says nothing of what that trait is or how a trait is inherited. It does not matter if the traits is inherited through genetics, or though oral tradition, or though writing, or though schooling or though plain old physical inheritance, i.e. handing over stuff from ancestor to descendant. The interesting part here is that those traits can easily be lost. Genetic traits are hard to gain but also hard to lose. These “soft” traits are easier gained, but also easier lost.  Of course, if we are to speak of non-genetic traits we must also challenge what we mean by “species”, because — looking at the nitty-gritty details of it — a species is defined by its common and inheritable traits. What if those traits are not only genes? What is then a species? And what happens when those traits can cross from one branch of the tree to another?

Yes. That started with the discovery of fire and the technology of cooking. Cooking releases more nutrients from food, enabling larger, more nutrient-hungry brains. Agriculture, one of the largest technological innovations in human history, accelerated that trend. Technology has shaped our evolution since the beginning.

When it comes to evolution, all sorts of things are “conceivable.” When you start with the belief that all forms of life evolved from microbes, that allows for an awful lot to happen in the future. Also, it should be noted that Darwin compared natural speciation to domestic breeding programs and their results. Technologies such as in-vitro fertilization may then be already affecting the ratios of alleles in our gene pool. We may also be exposing ourselves through various technologies to radiation and chemicals that are mutagenic, mostly affecting somatic cells that aren’t involved in evolution but any changes in reproductive cells would have some effect.
